\pard\f0\fs28 Plants generally similar to subsp. ({\b a}) but with glandular cilia on the sepals are found in the Alps, Pyrenees and Sierra Nevada, and have been distinguished as subsp. {\i glandulifera} Vacc., but they are united to subsp. ({\b a}) by too many intermediates to make recognition as a subspecies probable. Plants from unusually low altitude on the shores of the Bodensee, usually submerged in spring and early summer, have been named subsp. {\i amphibia} (Sünd.) Br.-Bl., but their rather slight morphological distinction was probably due to their peculiar environment. They appear to be now extinct.
